{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "The claim that thoughtlessness is a mass phenomenon is one that Arendt had already defended in The Human Condition.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "What is novel about Arendt's claim is her argument that there is a link between mass thoughtlessness and mass evil, the type of large-scale evil that can only be perpetrated with the support of the masses.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Arendt, however, remains cautious about recommending thoughtfulness per se as a panacea to modern mass thoughtlessness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "While thoughtlessness clearly 'has its perils', as the example of Eichmann illustrates, thoughtfulness has its own problems, as the example of Heidegger illustrates.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Arendt begins her account of thinking in The Life of the Mind with an attempt to answer this question.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "For Arendt, there are moral benefits to be gained from simply learning how to think, above and beyond those gained from learning what to think.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Arendt bases her account of thinking on Kant's distinction between reason (Vernunft), 'the urge to think and to understand', and intellect (Verstand), 'which desires and is capable of certain, verifiable knowledge'.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "With this distinction Arendt sees Kant as liberating thinking by differentiating it from knowledge, and thereby opening up room for reason to think about issues that lay beyond what can be known, but which remain of 'the greatest existential interest to man'.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Arendt claims that thinking and meaning remain forever unstable and non-definitive, whereas Kant claims that we can strike solid ground in practical matters through critical reflection and the recognition of the absolute value of humanity.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Critical thinking is 'representative' or 'enlarged' thinking, and this involves thinking through an issue from as many different standpoints as possible.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Critical thinking conditions the thinker against being swept along thoughtlessly by mass movements that can lead to evil.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Critical thinking has a further conditioning effect, as it sets the foundation for (but does not guarantee) representative judgment.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Good judgment requires the ability to put aside prejudices and appreciate the particularity of individual cases.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Arendt argues that a 'genuine' conscience is a by-product of the activity of thinking and not simply the presence of consciousness.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Conscience arises out of the dialectical nature of thinking, as in thinking 'I am both the one who asks and the one who answers', that is, I am two-in-one.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Arendt argues that conscience plays only a constraining role, by placing barriers in one's way and advising on the pain of being unable to live with oneself that one ought not to perform certain actions.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Arendt's account of conscience is phenomenological and descriptive, rather than normative.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Arendt understands Eichmann's thoughtlessness to be the norm in modern mass societies.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "The masses, on Arendt's story, are so alienated and thoughtless that they will blindly follow any set of mores, no matter how irrational or violent.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "Even so, Arendt's view that mass evil is perpetrated in large part by people who thoughtlessly cooperate, and have no intention of being either good or evil, remains a valid insight.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
