{
  "ADUs": {
    "1": {
      "text": "If there is one lesson that Hannah Arendt drew from her encounter with Adolf Eichmann in Jerusalem it was that the moral and political dangers of thoughtlessness had been grossly underestimated",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "2": {
      "text": "What is novel about Arendt's claim is her argument that there is a link between mass thoughtlessness and mass evil, the type of large-scale evil that can only be perpetrated with the support of the masses",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "3": {
      "text": "Critical thinking, according to Kant and according to Socrates, exposes itself to 'the test of free and open examination,' and this means that the more people participate in it, the better",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "4": {
      "text": "While all thinking is hidden and withdrawn, critical thinkers 'cannot endure living constantly in' the world of isolated thought",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "5": {
      "text": "Far more worrying are the dangers of nihilism, dogmatism and ideology that are an 'ever-present danger of thinking'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "6": {
      "text": "Critical thinking, in its openness to plurality, thereby conditions against evil by avoiding the twin dangers of common thoughtlessness and unethical professional thoughtfulness",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "7": {
      "text": "Arendt argues that conscience plays only a constraining role, by placing barriers in one's way and advising on the pain of being unable to live with oneself that one ought not to perform certain actions",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "8": {
      "text": "Arendt's account completely ignores this 'working through' or 'rebuilding' function of conscience, whereby we are compelled to compensate those we have wronged, so that we might come to live with ourselves in peace once again",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
